    "analysis": "<p>In highly asynchronous storage engines, <code>io_uring</code> is favored for its zero-copy, lockless completion path. However, when the rate of Completion Queue Entries (CQEs) generated by kernel I/O completions outpaces the application's ability to reap them, the completion queue overflows. Unlike the Submission Queue (SQ), which returns <code>-EBUSY</code> when full, CQ overflows are handled silently by the kernel backlogging finished events, or worse, dropping them if the kernel-side backlog overflows. This results in missing completions, stalled futures, and resource leaks.</p><p>By default, if the completion queue size is configured to match the submission queue size, any multi-stage I/O request (like linked SQEs) can easily cause CQE starvation or backlog buildup. When the backlog fills, the kernel delays processing pending SQEs, creating sudden, unpredictable tail latencies in storage engines under high write amplification.</p>",
